{"title_page": "In the Summertime", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = In the Summertime\n| cover      = MungoJerryInTheSummertime7InchSingleCover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Mungo Jerry]]\n| album      = [[Electronically Tested]]\n| B-side     = Mighty Man\n| released   = 1970\n| format     =\n| recorded   = {{unbulleted list|1970|Pye Recording Studios, [[Marble Arch]], London}}\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Skiffle]]<ref>{{cite news|first= Bill |last= Holdship |title= That summer feeling |newspaper= [[Metro Times]] |date= 17 June 2009 |url= http://www2.metrotimes.com/arts/story.asp?id=14086 |accessdate= 29 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|first= Moira |last= McCormick |title= Elfin's Listening-Post Towers Bring Children's Artists To Upscale Market |magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date= 18 May 1996 |volume= 108 |issue= 20 |page= 50 |issn= 0006-2510 |url= https://books.google.com/?id=uA0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA50&dq=%22skiffle%22}}</ref>\n| length     = 3:40\n| label      = [[Dawn Records|Dawn]]\n| writer     = [[Ray Dorset]]\n| producer   = Barry Murray\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Baby Jump]]\n| next_year  = 1971\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = In the Summertime (Mungo Jerry song).ogg\n | description = \"In the Summerime\"\n}}\n}}\n\"'''In the Summertime'''\" is the debut single by British rock band [[Mungo Jerry]]. Written and composed by its lead singer, [[Ray Dorset]], it celebrates the carefree days of summer. In 1970, it reached number one in charts around the world, including seven weeks on the [[UK Singles Chart]], two weeks on one of the [[RPM (magazine)|Canadian charts]], and number three on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] singles chart in the US. It became one of the [[List of best-selling singles|best-selling singles of all-time]], eventually selling 30 million copies.<ref>{{cite web|first= Craig |last= Harris |title= Ray Dorset \u2013 Artist Biography |website= [[AllMusic]] |accessdate= 20 January 2019 |url= https://www.allmusic.com/artist/ray-dorset-mn0000345252/biography}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= The essential summer mix |newspaper= [[The Guardian]] |date= 29 July 2006 |url= https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2006/jul/29/culturaltrips.pop}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first= Laura |last= Nightingale |title= Mungo Jerry celebrates 45 years of In the Summertime at Camberley Theatre |newspaper= [[Surrey Advertiser|Get Surrey]] |date= 7 October 2015 |accessdate= 10 February 2019 |url= https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/mungo-jerry-celebrates-45-years-10201428}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nDorset has said that the song only took ten minutes to write, which he did using a second-hand [[Fender Stratocaster]] while he was taking time off work from his regular job, working in a lab for [[Timex Group|Timex]].<ref>{{cite news|first= Peter |last= Robertson |title= Whatever happened to In The Summertime singer Mungo Jerry |newspaper= [[Daily Express]] |date= 26 April 2014 |accessdate= 9 July 2014 |url= http://www.express.co.uk/life-style/life/472160/Mungo-Jerry-sang-In-The-Summertime}}</ref>\n\nThe initial UK release was on [[Dawn Records]], a new label launched by [[Pye Records|Pye]]. It was unusual in that it was a [[maxi single]], playing at 33-1/3 rpm, whereas singles generally played at 45 rpm. It included an additional song also written and composed by Dorset, \"Mighty Man,\" on the A-side, and a much longer track, the [[Woody Guthrie]] song \"Dust Pneumonia Blues,\" on the B-side. As the record was sold in a picture sleeve, also not standard at the time, and only sold at a few pence more than the normal 45 rpm two-track single, it was considered value for money. A small quantity of 45 rpm discs on the Pye record label, with \"Mighty Man\" on the B-side, and without a picture sleeve, were pressed for use in [[jukebox]]es. These are now rare collector's items.\n\nIn 2012, Dorset sued his former management company Associated Music International, run by his former friend and business manager Eliot Cohen, claiming over \u00a32 million in [[royalties]] from the song that he believed had been withheld from him.<ref>{{cite web|title= Mungo Jerry Star Suing Over Alleged Unpaid Royalties |website= [[Contactmusic.com]] |date= 22 January 2012 |accessdate= 25 May 2014 |url= http://www.contactmusic.com/news/mungo-jerry-star-suing-over-alleged-unpaid-royalties_1285706}}</ref><!-- outcome unclear, so assuming out-of-court settlement with reporting restrictions-->\n\nIn an interview with Gary James, Dorset explained the origin of the \"motorcycle\" sound towards the false ending in the middle of the song: \"I said, 'We'll just get a recording of a motorcycle, stick it on the end of the song and then re-edit the front and then put the front off to the motorcycle so it starts up again.' But I couldn't find a motorcycle. Howard Barry, the engineer had an old, well, it wasn't old then, a [[Triumph Motor Company|Triumph]] sports car, which he drove past the studio while Barry Marrit was holding the microphone. So, he got the stereo effects from left to right or right to left, whatever. And that was it.\"<ref>{{cite interview|first= Ray |last= Dorset |interviewer= Gary James |title= Gary James' Interview With Ray Dorset Of Mungo Jerry |publisher= Classicbands.com |accessdate= 9 July 2014 |url= http://www.classicbands.com/MungoJerryInterview.html}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from the single [[liner notes]] for \"In the Summertime\".<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title= In the Summertime |others= Mungo Jerry |year= 1970 |url= https://www.discogs.com/release/1468468-In-The-Summertime/images |accessdate= 31 July 2017 |type= liner notes |publisher= [[Dawn Records|Dawn]]}}</ref>\n* [[Ray Dorset]] \u2013 [[lead vocalist|vocals]], [[electric guitar]], [[Acoustic guitar|6 string acoustic]], [[cabasa]], stomp\n* [[Paul King (Mungo Jerry)|Paul King]] \u2013 [[banjo]], [[Jug (instrument)|jug]]\n* Colin Earl \u2013 [[piano]]\n* Mike Cole \u2013 [[double bass|string bass]]\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1970)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Go-Set|Go-Set National Top 40]])<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Go-Set Australian charts \u2013 29 August 1970 |magazine= [[Go-Set]] |accessdate= 4 August 2013 |url= http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1970/19700829.html}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Australia No. 1 hits -- 1970's |website= World Charts |accessdate= 19 January 2014 |url= http://www.worldcharts.co.uk/chartfeatures/aus/aus70.htm |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140424142031/http://www.worldcharts.co.uk/chartfeatures/aus/aus70.htm |archivedate= 24 April 2014}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|1|artist=Mungo Jerry|song=In The Summertime|accessdate=4 August 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|1|artist=Mungo Jerry|song=In The Summertime|accessdate=4 August 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|1|chartid=4532|accessdate=4 August 2013}}\n|-\n|Denmark ([[IFPI Denmark|IFPI]])<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Billboard \u2013 Hits of the World |magazine= Billboard |date= 8 August 1970 |volume= 82 |issue= 32 |page= 49 |issn= 0006-2510 |url= https://books.google.com/?id=kSkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA49&dq=%22denmark%22}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|France (CIDD)<ref name=\"France\">{{cite magazine|title= Hits of the World |magazine= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date= 19 September 1970 |page= 61 |issn= 0006-2510 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=wCkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA61&dq=%22In+the+Summertime%22}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|1|artist=Mungo Jerry|song=In The Summertime|songid=153|accessdate=4 August 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|1|